"padding-top: 0.225em; padding-bottom: 0.298em;">n</span></span></span></span></span></span></span> ) in the free energy formula and in the two generalization errors. So it influences generalization but less than the learning coefficient.</p><p> Like the singular fluctuation, little is known about its role in real-world systems. Unlike the singular fluctuation, the multiplicity has a comparatively simple meaning. Given a polynomial that vanishes at some point <span><span class="mjpage"><span class="mjx-chtml"><span class="mjx-math" aria-label="x"><span class="mjx-mrow" aria-hidden="true"><span class="mjx-mi"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-math-I" style="padding-top: 0.225em; padding-bottom: 0.298em;">x</span></span></span></span></span></span></span> , the multiplicity at <span><span class="mjpage"><span class="mjx-chtml"><span class="mjx-math" aria-label="x"><span class="mjx-mrow" aria-hidden="true"><span class="mjx-mi"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-math-I" style="padding-top: 0.225em; padding-bottom: 0.298em;">x</span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is the the degree of the lowest order term in <span><span class="mjpage"><span class="mjx-chtml"><span class="mjx-math" aria-label="x"><span class="mjx-mrow" aria-hidden="true"><span class="mjx-mi"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-math-I" style="padding-top: 0.225em; padding-bottom: 0.298em;">x</span></span></span></span></span></span></span> , when using a coordinate system that centers <span><span class="mjpage"><span class="mjx-chtml"><span class="mjx-math" aria-label="x"><span class="mjx-mrow" aria-hidden="true"><span class="mjx-mi"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-math-I" style="padding-top: 0.225em; padding-bottom: 0.298em;">x</span></span></span></span></span></span></span> at the origin. </p><figure class="image"><img src="https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/uG7oJkyLBHEw3MYpT/rzmbkowonsm4lp5zy01a" srcset="https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/uG7oJkyLBHEw3MYpT/bsdvzy1islvfxn3icsgy 130w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/uG7oJkyLBHEw3MYpT/vhlflt47aubfya9zz08z 260w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/uG7oJkyLBHEw3MYpT/b1qudlfgm0sf1prh7qgz 390w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/uG7oJkyLBHEw3MYpT/arn8awzinxydgogxeyhi 520w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/uG7oJkyLBHEw3MYpT/vucesuifbypubivor3to 650w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/uG7oJkyLBHEw3MYpT/mjwijysge7g0wsdrguoo 780w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/uG7oJkyLBHEw3MYpT/alfr9guo4dqwktbx55in 910w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/uG7oJkyLBHEw3MYpT/qggvsuvsezpqozijeibu 1040w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/uG7oJkyLBHEw3MYpT/cxxu1lw24o6il4vhisbl 1170w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/uG7oJkyLBHEw3MYpT/qeeq5nnvgp6zvbh1qok6 1284w"><figcaption> Curves with multiplicity 2 at the origin. <a href="https://www1.maths.leeds.ac.uk/~pmtemf/files/BFK_Frobenius.pdf">Benito et al. (2012)</a></figcaption></figure><h3> Weight norm</h3><p> The weight norm is probably the most obvious alternative to explicit parameter count as a measure of model complexity. It&#39;s common knowledge that regularization terms like weight decay encourage simpler models that generalize better. Naturally, learning theorists have worked hard to obtain bounds that involve regularization strengths and weight norms (see, for example, <a href="http://proceedings.mlr.press/v40/Neyshabur15.pdf">Neyshabur et al. 2015</a> , <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1712.06541">Golowich et al. 2019</a> ). </p><figure class="image image_resized" style="width:80.77%"><img src="https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/uG7oJkyLBHEw3MYpT/qtyrhv609cmawt6bvzso" srcset="https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/uG7oJkyLBHEw3MYpT/mcz9wzwrz3qfbgemogvr 220w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/uG7oJkyLBHEw3MYpT/oslhlcsqajkeqr1rtmt4 440w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/uG7oJkyLBHEw3MYpT/sv2tfowsrxrsksss2v0c 660w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/uG7oJkyLBHEw3MYpT/zt5j7gaylzi1osc96fai 880w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/uG7oJkyLBHEw3MYpT/fsz4ayaotn0tqavdv9sg 1100w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/uG7oJkyLBHEw3MYpT/hhuwmgqmi5qribnpjxsb 1320w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/uG7oJkyLBHEw3MYpT/njpy8ijo0zqzgdcngw4m 1540w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/uG7oJkyLBHEw3MYpT/ayxjmbgkpw8a80xqlqqn 1760w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/uG7oJkyLBHEw3MYpT/pis3lil142jlg9ewrtm5 1980w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/uG7oJkyLBHEw3MYpT/enruixsoxtfkpoiulcxe 2124w"><figcaption> A larger weight-norm budget enables &quot;spikier&quot; fits. These two curves are constant multiples of each other. Which is &quot;simpler&quot;?</figcaption></figure><p> Unfortunately Zhang et al. also thought to test whether neural networks can fit random noise <i>in the presence of regularization</i> . They can, which means that weight norm alone is not enough to explain observed generalization performance. Incorporating weight norms might lead to tighter bounds, but these are marginal improvements and not enough to resolve the mystery.</p><p> Formally, this is because the weight norm is a lower order contribution to the free energy than the learning coefficient and multiplicity. After the multiplicity term, there&#39;s a stochastic term <span><span class="mjpage"><span class="mjx-chtml"><span class="mjx-math" aria-label="F^R(\xi)"><span class="mjx-mrow" aria-hidden="true"><span class="mjx-msubsup"><span class="mjx-base" style="margin-right: -0.106em;"><span class="mjx-mi"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-math-I" style="padding-top: 0.446em; padding-bottom: 0.298em; padding-right: 0.106em;">F</span></span></span> <span class="mjx-sup" style="font-size: 70.7%; vertical-align: 0.513em; padding-left: 0.266em; padding-right: 0.071em;"><span class="mjx-mi" style=""><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-math-I" style="padding-top: 0.446em; padding-bottom: 0.298em;">R</span></span></span></span> <span class="mjx-mo"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R" style="padding-top: 0.446em; padding-bottom: 0.593em;">(</span></span> <span class="mjx-mi"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-math-I" style="padding-top: 0.519em; padding-bottom: 0.519em; padding-right: 0.005em;">ξ</span></span> <span class="mjx-mo"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R" style="padding-top: 0.446em; padding-bottom: 0.593em;">)</span></span></span></span></span></span></span> related to randomness in draws of the dataset and a constant order term <span><span class="mjpage"><span class="mjx-chtml"><span class="mjx-math" aria-label="o_p(1)"><span class="mjx-mrow" aria-hidden="true"><span class="mjx-msubsup"><span class="mjx-base"><span class="mjx-mi"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-math-I" style="padding-top: 0.225em; padding-bottom: 0.298em;">o</span></span></span> <span class="mjx-sub" style="font-size: 70.7%; vertical-align: -0.212em; padding-right: 0.071em;"><span class="mjx-mi" style=""><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-math-I" style="padding-top: 0.225em; padding-bottom: 0.446em;">p</span></span></span></span> <span class="mjx-mo"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R" style="padding-top: 0.446em; padding-bottom: 0.593em;">(</span></span> <span class="mjx-mn"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R" style="padding-top: 0.372em; padding-bottom: 0.372em;">1</span></span> <span class="mjx-mo"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R" style="padding-top: 0.446em; padding-bottom: 0.593em;">)</span></span></span></span></span></span></span> which contains the contribution of the prior. With a standard choice of Gaussian prior, this is where the weight norm would show up. So the weight norm has influence on behavior and generalization, but less than you might expect in a Bayesian setting.</p><h1> Thermodynamics of generalization</h1><h2> Internal model selection</h2><p> In what sense does this last set of complexity measures relate to model subclasses?</p><p> To reveal the link, let us coarse-grain the weight space into a collection of compact subsets <span><span class="mjpage"><span class="mjx-chtml"><span class="mjx-math" aria-label="W_\alpha"><span class="mjx-mrow" aria-hidden="true"><span class="mjx-msubsup"><span class="mjx-base" style="margin-right: -0.104em;"><span class="mjx-mi"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-math-I" style="padding-top: 0.446em; padding-bottom: 0.298em; padding-right: 0.104em;">W</span></span></span> <span class="mjx-sub" style="font-size: 70.7%; vertical-align: -0.212em; padding-right: 0.071em;"><span class="mjx-mi" style=""><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-math-I" style="padding-top: 0.225em; padding-bottom: 0.298em;">α</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> that cover <span><span class="mjpage"><span class="mjx-chtml"><span class="mjx-math" aria-label="\mathcal W"><span class="mjx-mrow" aria-hidden="true"><span class="mjx-texatom"><span class="mjx-mrow"><span class="mjx-mi"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-cal-R" style="padding-top: 0.446em; padding-bottom: 0.372em; padding-right: 0.046em;">W</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> . For now, the particular choice of partitioning is arbitrary ( <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=60Sd0D-D960&amp;list=PL4vaU_gO_6LJctKxh0BfZ05gK-LLnlgTM">up to a few technical conditions</a> ). This allows us to re-express the free energy <span><span class="mjpage"><span class="mjx-chtml"><span class="mjx-math" aria-label="F_n"><span class="mjx-mrow" aria-hidden="true"><span class="mjx-msubsup"><span class="mjx-base" style="margin-right: -0.106em;"><span class="mjx-mi"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-math-I" style="padding-top: 0.446em; padding-bottom: 0.298em; padding-right: 0.106em;">F</span></span></span> <span class="mjx-sub" style="font-size: 70.7%; vertical-align: -0.212em; padding-right: 0.071em;"><span class="mjx-mi" style=""><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-math-I" style="padding-top: 0.225em; padding-bottom: 0.298em;">n</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> as a combination over the <i><strong>local</strong></i> <strong>free energies</strong> <span><span class="mjpage"><span class="mjx-chtml"><span class="mjx-math" aria-label="F_n(W_\alpha)"><span class="mjx-mrow" aria-hidden="true"><span class="mjx-msubsup"><span class="mjx-base" style="margin-right: -0.106em;"><span class="mjx-mi"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-math-I" style="padding-top: 0.446em; padding-bottom: 0.298em; padding-right: 0.106em;">F</span></span></span> <span class="mjx-sub" style="font-size: 70.7%; vertical-align: -0.212em; padding-right: 0.071em;"><span class="mjx-mi" style=""><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-math-I" style="padding-top: 0.225em; padding-bottom: 0.298em;">n</span></span></span></span> <span class="mjx-mo"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R" style="padding-top: 0.446em; padding-bottom: 0.593em;">(</span></span> <span class="mjx-msubsup"><span class="mjx-base" style="margin-right: -0.104em;"><span class="mjx-mi"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-math-I" style="padding-top: 0.446em; padding-bottom: 0.298em; padding-right: 0.104em;">W</span></span></span> <span class="mjx-sub" style="font-size: 70.7%; vertical-align: -0.212em; padding-right: 0.071em;"><span class="mjx-mi" style=""><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-math-I" style="padding-top: 0.225em; padding-bottom: 0.298em;">α</span></span></span></span> <span class="mjx-mo"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R" style="padding-top: 0.446em; padding-bottom: 0.593em;">)</span></span></span></span></span></span></span> of each subclass (with an adjusted prior <span><span class="mjpage"><span class="mjx-chtml"><span class="mjx-math" aria-label="\varphi_\alpha"><span class="mjx-mrow" aria-hidden="true"><span class="mjx-msubsup"><span class="mjx-base"><span class="mjx-mi"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-math-I" style="padding-top: 0.225em; padding-bottom: 0.519em;">φ</span></span></span> <span class="mjx-sub" style="font-size: 70.7%; vertical-align: -0.212em; padding-right: 0.071em;"><span class="mjx-mi" style=""><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-math-I" style="padding-top: 0.225em; padding-bottom: 0.298em;">α</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> and restricted domain of integration):</p> <span><span class="mjpage mjpage__block"><span class="mjx-chtml MJXc-display" style="text-align: center;"><span class="mjx-math" aria-label="\begin{align} F_n &amp;= -\log \sum\limits_\alpha \int_{W_\alpha} p(D_n|w)\,\varphi_\alpha(w),\mathrm d w, \\ &amp;= -\log \sum\limits_\alpha e^{-F_n(W_\alpha)} \\ &amp;\approx \min_\alpha F_n(W_\alpha). \end{align}"><span class="mjx-mrow" aria-hidden="true"><span class="mjx-mtable" style="vertical-align: -3.052em; padding: 0px 0.167em;"><span class="mjx-table"><span class="mjx-mtr" style="height: 2.633em;"><span class="mjx-mtd" style="padding: 0px 0px 0px 0px; text-align: right; width: 1.103em;"><span class="mjx-mrow" style="margin-top: 0.386em;"><span class="mjx-msubsup"><span class="mjx-base" style="margin-right: -0.106em;"><span class="mjx-mi"><span class="mjx-c